explanation:
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - The call graph shows the target calls this (via the OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET macro). You must inspect its behavior/side-effects (e.g. error handling, return values) to know whether obtaining impl is required and can affect program behavior (removal might be dead).
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - Macro/inline used to map token -> table entry; its expansion determines whether it has side effects (bounds checks, error logging) so is required to decide if the mapping call is meaningful or dead.
OS_impl_dir_table - The object table referenced by the macro; its structure/content could make the lookup essential (or a no-op) and is needed to see if the lookup and subsequent use of the entry are relevant.
OS_impl_dir_internal_record_t - Definition is required to know what impl->dp is (type, volatile qualifiers, etc.) and whether accessing impl->dp has side effects (e.g. volatile, accessor semantics) that would make the code non-dead.
OS_object_token_t - Token type used as input; its semantics might influence whether the table lookup is meaningful or redundant.
os_dirent_t - The destination type (dirent) definition, in particular the FileName member and its size, is needed to judge whether the strncpy and NUL termination operations have observable effect (non-dead).
struct dirent - Source dirent definition (d_name member) is needed to know what is being read from readdir and whether copying that data changes program-visible state.
readdir - The function call may have observable side effects (advances DIR internal pointer, interacts with underlying filesystem state). Its semantics must be known to determine whether the call (and thus surrounding code) is dead.
strncpy - The copy operation semantics (possible side effects, behavior on overlapping, return value ignored) are relevant to decide if the copy into dirent->FileName is meaningful or removable.
OS_ERROR and OS_SUCCESS - The return constants used by the function; their meaning/usage in callers determines whether the function's behavior (returning success/failure) affects program behavior and so whether the function body is dead.

These symbols together provide the types, table lookup mechanics, I/O call semantics, and return semantics needed to decide whether any executed operations in OS_DirRead_Impl could be removed without changing observable program behavior (the core of the MISRA dead-code analysis).
